Custom Resource Definitions (CRDs) allow you to define your own Kubernetes resource types.

For example, Kubernetes doesnâ€™t have a built-in object for â€œDatabaseâ€ or â€œCacheCluster.â€ With a CRD, you can create:
$ kubectl get databases
$ kubectl describe cacheclusters
CRDs act just like native resourcesâ€”versioned, namespaced, and supported by RBAC and the Kubernetes API.

